{{Infobox body of water |name = Sibutu&nbsp;Passage |location = [[Sulu Archipelago]] ([[Philippines]]) and [[Borneo]] |pushpin_map = Philippines | pushpin_label_position = | pushpin_map_alt = | pushpin_map_caption = Location within the Philippines |coordinates = {{coord|4|49|55.92|N|119|41|35.88|E|region:PH|display=inline,title}} | coor_pinpoint = |part_of = | image = | alt = | caption = |type = [[strait]] }}
'''Sibutu Passage''' is a deep channel some 18 miles (29&nbsp;km) wide that separates [[Borneo]] from the [[Sulu Archipelago]]. It has a deep sill allowing entry of deep water into the Sulu basin while connecting the [[Sulu Sea]] with the [[Sulawesi Sea]] that feeds from the [[Pacific Ocean]] by the [[Mindanao Current]].
Although [[H. Otley Beyer]] argued in favor of a [[Models of migration to the Philippines|settlement of the Philippines]] across [[land bridge]]s during the [[last glacial period|last ice age]], modern [[bathymetry|bathymetric]] soundings have shown that the centers of the Sibutu Passage and the [[Mindoro Strait]] are both deep enough that they probably still existed at that time, although the Sulu and other [[Philippine Islands]] beyond were one connected island. If verified, therefore, the [[Callao Man]] would have needed to have crossed open sea to reach the islands.
==References== * ''Philippine Islands Sailing Directions'', third edition of the bulletin prepared in the office of the [[U.S. Coast and Geodetic Survey]] at [[Manila]] by Harry L. Ford, nautical expert (Washington, DC: Bureau of Printing, 1906), p.&nbsp;171 * Lambert Anthony B. Meñez, Cesar L. Villanoy and Laura T. David. "Movement of Water Across Passages Connecting Philippine Inland Sea Basins" (Marine Science Institute, University of the Philippines, November 6, 2006)
==External links== *[https://web.archive.org/web/20090627090220/http://encarta.msn.com/map_701545826/Sibutu_Passage.html Map of Sibutu Passage (channel), Philippines] Encarta - MSN *[http://geology.com/world/malaysia-satellite-image.shtml Malaysia Map - Malaysia Satellite Image] - Geology.com
