The '''Swedish Society for Anthropology and Geography''' ({{lang-sv|Svenska Sällskapet för Antropologi och Geografi}}) is a scientific [[learned society]] founded in [[Sweden]] in 1877. It was established after a rearrangement of related sections of the Anthropological Society, itself formed in 1873 by [[Hjalmar Stolpe]], [[Hans Hildebrand]], [[Oscar Montelius]], and [[Gustaf Retzius]].<ref>{{cite journal |last=Culin |first=Stewart |title=Hjalmar Stolpe |journal=American Anthropologist |publisher=American Anthropological Association |date=January–March 1906 |volume=8 |issue=1 |page=151 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xnl0AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA151&dq=%22Swedish+Society+for+Anthropology+and+Geography |doi=10.1525/aa.1906.8.1.02a00160}}</ref>
The society functions as a link between science and the public, especially in the subjects of [[anthropology]] and [[geography]]. It awards research fellowships, organizes excursions and lectures, hands out awards such as the Vega Medal and Retzius Medal. In 1880, it began publishing the Swedish yearbook ''[[Ymer (journal)|Ymer]]'' and it has published the international journal ''[[Geografiska Annaler]]'' since 1919. The journal is divided between [[physical geography]] and [[human geography]]. In 2018, it established ''[[kritisk etnografi]]''.
== Awards given by the society == The society created the ''[[Vega (ship)|Vega]]'' Medal in 1881 on the occasion of Adolf Erik Nordenskiöld's return to Stockholm, after he had discovered the [[Northern Sea Route|North East Passage]]. Since then, the Vega Medal has been awarded to a physical geographer roughly every three years. In the intervening years, the society awarded the [[Anders Retzius]] Medal to a human geographer or an anthropologist.<ref>{{cite journal | last1 = Helmfrid | first1 = S | year = 2004 | title = Geography in Sweden | url = | journal = Belgeo | volume = 5 | issue = 1| page = 172 }}</ref> In 2015, however, it was decided that awarding a medal named after Retzius wasn't appropriate anymore, considering that his racial studies (that included the active collection of [[skull]]s from [[indigenous people]]s) are met with disapproval by modern anthropologists.<ref>{{cite news |last=Kleen |first=Björn af |date=2015-03-07 |title=Stopp för medalj till rasforskarens minne |url=http://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/stopp-for-medalj-till-rasforskarens-minne-1/ |newspaper=Dagens Nyheter |location= |access-date=2015-04-02 }}</ref> Instead, the SSAG medal was given to [[Didier Fassin]] in 2016. The awards are handed out by the king of Sweden on 24 April, the anniversary of Nordenskiöld's return to Stockholm.
